messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full request path:
- /admin/users/{user}

All HTTP methods allowed:
- all methods: false

Per-method allowance (based on the route definitions and controller methods):
- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: false
- PUT: true
- DELETE: false
- PATCH: true

Explanation / reasoning:
- routes/admin.php registers a resource route for "users": Route::resource('users', UserController::class)->only(['index', 'edit', 'update']);
- The resource() call with only(['index','edit','update']) creates these standard resource routes:
  - index -> GET /users (users.index)
  - edit -> GET /users/{user}/edit (users.edit)
  - update -> PUT/PATCH /users/{user} (users.update)
- The controller implements index, edit and update, matching the three routes above; there is no show, store, or destroy implemented/registered for users, so /users/{user} does not accept GET, POST, or DELETE.
- The application code uses route names like 'admin.users.edit' (see redirect()->route('admin.users.edit', $user)), which indicates the admin routes are loaded with an 'admin.' name prefix and an 'admin' URI prefix (typical Laravel pattern and implied by the route names). Therefore the effective URI prefix is /admin, making the full update path /admin/users/{user} (and edit would be /admin/users/{user}/edit, index /admin/users).
- The update route (users.update) supports both PUT and PATCH according to Laravel's resource route mapping â€” therefore PUT and PATCH are accepted for /admin/users/{user}.
- I marked HEAD, OPTIONS, TRACE, POST, GET, DELETE as false because there is no code-level route registration for those methods on /admin/users/{user} (the controller/routes do not define a GET (show), POST (store), DELETE (destroy), or explicit HEAD/OPTIONS/TRACE handler). Per your instruction I did not assume framework implicit behavior (for example Laravel often responds to HEAD automatically via the GET route); only explicitly registered resource methods were considered.
